description:
Greetings Ashish and Namrata! 

 

Please see below for interesting question from OSD.  This feels like the natural next step for our screening tools:  Compare results/score over-time.  For HOOS/KOOS this would be a comparison of pre-op and post-op (and perhaps even several measurements in the post-op period).  We want to see an improving score to demonstrate surgical success.

 

  • This link describes scoring the HOOS JR. (similar to what we do with ODI and DAS calculator)  https://www.hss.edu/files/HOOS-JR-Scoring-Instructions-2017.pdf

 

  • This link describes scoring the PHQ-9:  https://www.med.umich.edu/1info/FHP/practiceguides/depress/score.pdf

 

Let’s discuss!

 

Thanks,

 

Julie

 

From: Kelly Payette <kelly@dallasortho.net>
Sent: Sunday, February 3, 2019 6:25 PM
To: Julie Lundberg <jlundberg@triarqhealth.com>
Subject: Question

 

Hi Julie,

 

Do you know of a company who can take my HOOS/KOOS data and actually report back to me on it? I know there are a lot of platforms out there, just not really sure who and where to obtain that information from. We are doing all of the work by capturing the data, we just aren_t analyzing it and need to be.

 

 

Thank you,

 

Kelly Payette, MBA, BSHM

Orthopaedic Specialists of Dallas

Chief Administrative Officer

project_name: Due to the many reports of slow printing (mainly with Clinical Charts/Batches), we have begun deploying TS Print at our own expense.  Each TS license costs us 399.00 USD.  As you can see, in a situation like Ortho Michigan (8 Terminal Servers) or SAPA (5 Terminal Servers) this cost can add up quickly.  A major part of the issue, is that users are forced to wait for the print job to complete (may take up to 20 minutes for larger jobs) before they can continue working within gloSuite.
description: To alleviate this cost for TS Print and to make our users workflow more efficient, we would like to the Development Team to please consider the suggested change for printing in the next release: Today, when a clinical chart/batch is printed, the user must wait for the print processing to complete before they can continue on with any other work within gloPM/EMR.  WORKFLOW: User initiates print job à gloSuite processes the print job (Appears to be a freeze to the user) à Processing completes, now the user can continue working. Print job is processing in a separate thread allowing user access back to main gloSuite application. Proposed change is to move printing processes to a separate thread: WORKFLOW: User initiates print job à Message to User: Print job is processing, You may continue working while print job processes.
HEDIS and NCQA for private payer certification

Clinical Quality Language is a Health Level Seven International authoring language standard that’s intended to be human readable. It is part of the effort to harmonize standards used for electronic clinical quality measures (eCQMs) and clinical decision support (CDS).    CQL provides the ability to express logic that is human readable yet structured enough for processing a query electronically. CQL is the expression logic used in Health Quality Measure Format beginning with the eCQMs intended for implementation in calendar year 2019.    CQL replaces the logic expressions previously defined in the Quality Data Model (QDM) and QDMinfo-icon (beginning with v5.3) includes only the conceptual model for defining the data elements (the data model). Measure authors with access to the Measure Authoring Tool (MATinfo-icon) can use the tool to author measures using CQL.
